Student Veterans of America has started Veterans Opinion Survey. This new research initiative takes the benefits of public opinion research and applies them to the veteran community to help give veterans a stronger voice in policy discussions and decisions. These monthly surveys provide feedback from the veteran community to public officials and decision makers on the important issues and priorities facing our nation's veterans.

End:
I quit the 10th grade to join the Army in 1984. I received my GED in 1986 at Camp Casey Korea, and I didn't start my college career until 21 years later. I know have 3 degrees inclding my MBA. My transition into acedemia was tough and I wish that I had known more about what portunities were available to me. 

Now I work at a private university supporting veterans and their families but I struggle to get them to come to me. I could share so much of what I have learned, I could make their lives so much better than mine if they would reach out, but they hardly ever do. I try to think back and ask myself; what would have brought you to the table with you. And I don't know what to say. For me, it was a friend who got me started on my journey. But I am not their friend and I cannot  figure out how to get acquainted with them to possibly become a friend. Especially in this time of Covid-19. 

Anyway, my academic career was rough, but I enjoyed it. I landed some amazing jobs like with the US Forest Service, and the United States Fish and Wildlife Service. I resigned to come back to my almamater because at the time Sequestration wasn't allowing me a chance at a full time position. I was on 13 month contracts and I was tired of wondering every Christmas, should I be spending money on gifts, or saving for January when I am unemployed? 

During my academic career and new staff career I was actively engaged in many things such as: Society of American Foresters (SAF) Association of the United States Army (AUSA) I was even a chapter president,  VFW, American Legion, I was on the Washington State Military Transition Council Higher Education Working Group, I attended Chamber of Commerce events, Washington Department of Veterans Affairs events, and a lot more. 

Now I am still working but looking for a new job because I am worried that my school will let me go to stay afloat. I am so blessed, I cannot complain. The transition continues.

End: SVA and the college experience have saved my life. After losing my job, my wife, and being diagnosed with PTSD, anxiety, and depression... I wasn't sure if I was useful anymore. In the academic environment, I learned there are still young veterans coming home who need someone there for them. I also learned there are is an entire civilian population which has a great deal to learn from the veteran community. The SVA leadership institute and summit in 2019 really rocked my world. I realized I am not alone. There are other veterans, just like me, who are making great achievements for their self, their family, and their community. The mission isn't over... it simply changed.

Although, it is much like dealing with VA health services, where you never know what you are going to get. VA health services treat their veterans as if they were a problem to begin with and that may not always be the case with VA student services. I am glad that I have more correspondence with advisors through the University and VA student services are there if only to handle issues with payment.

End: The post 9/11 GI bill has been great.  The student veterans' resource at my university have been very timely/responsive.  I would like to share some thoughts: 1.  Online programs have obviously grown/becoming more of the norm - why is it that the housing allowance is different for on-site programs vice on-line?  Either way you need a place to live.  2.  My current program, at certain points, will only allow a student to take courses that equate to part-time student status; this is beyond the student's control - yet again impacting the housing allowance - we still have to pay rent/mortgage. Final note - intent (hopefully for most) is to be a contributing member to society, the better the employment the more taxes we pay the more we support our country; so why do my 2 points above, & I am sure there are other nuances, exist?  I realize there's a short-term savings to GI funds with these rules but what about the long-term outcome?

End: One of the most difficult challenges I have seen student veterans face includes navigating the VA system. Many schools do not release any funds such as scholarships, financial aid, or student loans until the GI Bill has paid their accounts. This results in a delayed payments and many student veterans discover this situation the hard way. If you do not know a fellow veteran or not well connected with your campus veteran center, then the first couple of weeks of class will be stressful. This can compound mental health issues and underlying medical conditions serve connected or otherwise. Veterans have a difficult time focusing on classes when they are struggling financially.

End:
I have had many, but my most memorable would probably be promoting legislative changes for student veterans with SVA National in DC earlier this year.

Unrelated to experiences, but still relevant, I think it might be beneficial to allow individuals that participate in SVA surveys to select more than one option for military affiliation if possible. I recognize this could potentially skew data and might be challenging to logistically execute, but I think it might give students like myself that have more than one affiliation the opportunity to be fully represented. Although I am a Reservist currently, prior to that I served 11 years active duty and then had several months of separation before I joined the Reserves. I am also the spouse of an active duty submariner. So, normally I identify as a Veteran, a Reservist, and a Military Spouse when given the option. Just some food for thought, but I appreciate all the effort your organization puts in to improve the lives of military affiliated students, and I know things will only get better.

End: Was a very hard transition for me when I came to higher education. I was out of service and working the first job I could get. I would go to interview and was told "you have tons of experience, just no degree to back it." I would get this answer from almost every recruiter or from the people interview with. I continued at my dead end job, while searching for better opportunities for 3 years There was also eight month of time I was homeless.  Then I finally sought out higher education and was accepted to a university. This transition to university was not smooth to say the least. I went from full time job to full time school so that I would get the maximum benefits financially and not really have to work while in school. I had to drop all of my classes midway through because I was not able to keep up with classes of ready for the course load. The net semester I started again and got with the Disability Resource Center on campus to help. And excelled that semester and every semester since. I have even rose to become the Chapter President.

End: Being a 40 year old Disabled Persian Gulf War Veteran has been challenging. Luckily I have nephews and niece's who are the same age as my classmates so -- me trying to make new friends with 19 and 20 year olds has not been too tough but not very easy especially when i am older than most instructors. Luckily i still love Playstaion 4 video games, I love surfing for exercise and stress relief, I still love listening to music just as much as I did the whole time thru my Military service to give me strength and comfort. In fact i remember listening to all kinds of music up to boot camp entry -- thru service enlistment -- and getting honorably discharged back into the civilian world. I still re visit these tools everyday to re-focus myself to remind me of how lucky I am that Smart, Strong, Brave, Loving Americans fought and served America so that other Americans could continue. I am also very lucky that I was stationed on a ship where alcohol was forbidden on board.

End: Traditional Universities focus on developing resources to accommodate Veterans; however, they lack the emphasis on accommodating adult learners. (Veteran and adult learner have deep a deep intersectionality.) As such, it has been incredibly challenging and lonely in trying to start my academic life back up in my 30s when the entire learning experience is based around an 18 year old that was in high school 3 months prior. If we want to change Veteran's lives academically, we need to focus more on them being adult learners (looking forward) than we do their Veteran experience (looking backward).

End: Due to medical conditions and/or other factors a VA mandated "full time" schedule can impact how well a student learns. Especially when the full time requirements outlined by the VA conflict with the guidance from the institution of higher learning. For example, the VA mandates nine (9) credits to be considered a full time masters student and if the institution recommends only six (6) credits due to the rigor of the program it can be problematic for the veteran. Especially if he/she is diagnosed with a medical condition that can impact the way he/she learns. The VA standard for full time should coincide with the recommendation of the institution or at the very least consider the medical conditions of the veteran.

Transfer reason_12_TEXT: Simply going where there is least resistance.  As in the cheapest.
Degree_7_TEXT: As far as I can get without having to pay for it.
Fin aid: GI Bill (any version / chapter),Federal Pell grant,Out of my own pocket,Personal savings
LinkedIn: Yes, but have not recently updated it
End: After serving for 7 years, I greatly appreciate the 36 months of benefits.  However, after being enrolled in college full-time, I still do not understand why we pay for it.  The education I have received from public institutions is worse than what I received from the military.  Faculty have already proven how little they care about students, yet they are being paid by students.  The only thing being taught now days is sacrifice.  You have to spend money to make money.  We all know we have to work hard to see results, but why make the work harder on us??? I was taught in the military to work smarter and not harder... Increasing the value of education only makes it harder to graduate and decreasing the value only lowers our education.  Schools have become businesses that care more about the curriculum and profit rather than if the students are comprehending what is being taught.  Everything comes with a cost, what are we willing to pay for something that is free?  It doesn't leave a good impression on people to make them pay to better themselves.  No response needed.

I remember when I first started to attend classes back in 1992, I was a non-traditional student, taking classes at night full time. I had my wife, who did not work at the time, and two children at home while attending classes and working a full-time job. Then, unfortunately, my time in service got in the way of the future I envisioned the education I was working would provide. When I could not get any assistance with my issues from the VA at the time, I dropped out of school and focused on keeping my family fed. Back then, there was nothing in the way of what I see and have experienced today. 

As a student today, there is much available to students. However, as a very non-traditional student being mid-career aged, at a public university, I find myself out of sorts with the college experience. I think that it is probably proper in many respects; it is not like someone of my age should be joining a frat for example.  It many ways, because the education system is designed around the young and inexperienced, I feel out of place.  Likely a symptom that my peers are generally younger than my children with a few exceptions. My life experience also gets in the way of the general instruction methods of the professors as it is also designed around the inexperienced. I hear similar things from the veterans that are younger also, so it leads me to believe that the experiences veterans have are the reason over age, although it is compounded I believe when one has reached the point of middle-age. Additionally, the resources are not designed or dedicated to an aged student. For example, when looking into grants, many are unavailable to me because of age. Yet the affordability of education is compounded by being established in life, with less working years ahead of me than behind me, a house, cars, and the rest of the bills that most working adults have. 

So in general, I feel options and opportunities are more limited to an aged student.

At my school there were no veterans services when I began. This lacking, was an incredible stress. My school was the only 4-year institution without a Veterans Specific Space. While we still do not have a Veterans Service Officer we have made significant improvements. 

The SVA has great room for improvement. The Leadership Institute(LI) provided more financial and leadership support than the SVA. The LI printed marketing material, provided leadership guidance and assisted in promoting Veteran Issues. The SVA was silent. 

I highly recommend develop regional coordinators that assist SVA chapters grow, coordinate advocacy efforts, conduct networking events and fund raising. 

Need to include retiree as an option.

End: When I was medically retired from the Army Reserve, I was told that I was entitled to be reeducated to the level of current education (AOC 66F, CRNA, Masters Degree) in a field of choice.  But this year I have been told repeatedly that I will not be given further education beyond my Bachelors's degree.  I am told that studies have been done that indicate that I would be financially better off and job market more competitive with a master's degree but that the vocational rehabilitation program will not pay for a master's degree even if I fail to gain employment.  I find this to be completely unacceptable on the part of the Veterans Administration and The United States of Army.  My ability to provide for my family has been taken away from me as I can no longer provide for them as an Anesthesia Provider simply because my nervous system becomes overloaded in cases of high stress.  I was promised a career that was parallel to my previous career in terms of education.  I am being denied access to those resources and repeatedly reminded by my counselor of the same that not only triggers my sense of failure but also my contiuned lack of support from my own conuntry.

End: I have broke down on many occasions because companies wouldn’t hire me during my undergraduate degree. I applied for 2 year and talked to over 600+ different mentors to prepare me. It has caused my depression to get worse and worse and I’m afraid of telling my own psychologist that it makes me think about suicide daily. My friends and family don’t even know this about me. I’m tired of my skills not being recognized for the hard work I put in. All I want is a chance at life. If anyone seriously wants the veteran suicide rate go down and this even includes the stress that students veterans are constantly under, give them a chance. We that choose to go college after our service look for more, but all we receive is the same or less as other traditional students. My grades were significantly affected by the lack of support from companies to let me assist in an internship because I spent an average of 4 hours a day just looking and applying for internships. I would say I’m not as upset as I am disappointed. This takes a lot for me to say because I spent night after night crying about it and it has negatively my love life, personal life, dating life, social life, and my family life. This is why I went to grad school because I’m tired of not being enough. I have a goal for my future and I just want to help other veterans succeed like I’m going to do. If anyone has any questions about this, call me personally because I’m ready to have the conversation. Something needs to change. -Drake

Just to clarify - I live together with mother of my twin girls, but she and I are not in romantic relationship with each other. We are not married. However, we are technically domestic partners through her work, so I can get on her health insurance. We file taxes separately. She does not claim  and has never claimed me as a dependent, but she does claim both girls. She files as head of household. 
 My total time in National Guard was Illinois Army National Guard, infantry unit, from 1986-1993. I then joined the Wisconsin Air National Guard from 1993-2007. 
 For part of my Guard time, from 1 October 2001 - 31 August 2002, I was on a Title 10 active duty tour home station in support of Operation Noble Eagle, post 9/11. I also did an AD short tour from about 31 May 2002 - 15 July 2002 in support of Operation Southern Watch, Prince Sultan Air Base, Saudi Arabia. 
 I earned my J.D. from Northern Illinois University in 1991. I did have student loan debt from law school, which has long since been paid off. Part of my student loan debt was repaid through the Student Loan Repayment Program (SLRP) for being in a critical skill MOS (infantry) in the IL ARNG. 
 Most recently, I earned a associate's degree in Child Development from LA Harbor College, using my Post 9/11 GI Bill for part of that time. I earned the A.D. in spring 2019. 
 Right now, since fall 2018, I have been working as a Special Education Assistant, helping students with special needs at a Career & Transition Center through LA Unified School District. 
 Hope that all sort of explains my situation, which might have gotten lost in some of the survey questions. 
 I am working toward a program to become a certified special education teacher with LAUSD.

I started school not too long after I ETSed out of the Army and just had a horrible experience. I hated being around these happy-go-lucky civilian college students so much, I'd drink every single day prior to the first class and would run home to keep drinking before my next class. Daytime college students just annoyed the shit out of me and I was constantly fantasizing reaching for a knife on my person and shoving it into their throats. At this time, I lived with my hanai mom and, with her helplessly seeing me going down this negative spiral, she threatened to have me committed because it hurt her so much to watch me fall into despair. My grades eventually fell and I had to take a break from school to focus on coming back from whatever emotional hellhole I'd unknowingly crawled into. I started seeing a psychiatrist, got a little better, and when I was ready to do school again, decided to switch universities and enter their night program instead. This time, things were much better. I kept my grades up and was able to graduate with a BA on the honor roll.

I'm writing this because I believe it is important for other student veterans to understand that readjusting to civilian life takes a lot of effort; the only way you can truly succeed is if you're motivated to do it for yourself, and not because anyone expects it of you.

My experiences as a student-veteran are to many to list in the space provided. One thing that I will say is as a TWO-TIME HONORABLY DISCHARGED VETERAN of both the US Air Force and U.S. Navy; there is no way in hell that I or any other veteran should have to pay for our education. Why was I NEVER afforded educational benefits after my discharge from the Navy?  I tell you why; because the yeoman at my last duty station aboard the USS Sierra AD-18 out of Charleston, So. Carolina, had me and other sailors sign certain papers that took our educational benefits away in exchange for cash at discharge. 

Stupid me, I spent 3 years on a ship that was welded to the pier that never went anywhere. Until my last year of enlistment the powers that be decided to send our old tin bucket of a destroyer-tender on a 6-month deployment (IO/Med Cruise).  When we got back to our home port it was 2 days before Christmas 1982.  My finance and our 4 month old son was waiting on the pier when we moored.  All I could think of was liberty call after a 6 month deployment and my new son and soon to be wife and making money. So after the holidays the paperwork started for my discharge. It was at that time the yeoman gave me thousand of dollars; which was a culmination of all pay due me and money I had taken from each paycheck for my educational needs once out of the Navy.  However, I was so excited to be getting out after 4 years of service; knowing I also served in the US Air Force prior to serving in the Navy.  All I wanted to do was start my family and get on with my civilian life.  

There should NEVER be any condition or situation where any veteran has to borrow money and take out both subsidized and unsubsidized loans to pay for his/her college education. We paid our debt to society be serving our country. We the veterans of the country make up less than 2% of ALL people in the US. who have served in the military.  If anyone deserves a break on education, healthcare, housing, and employment it should be my fellow veterans and me.  We did what 98% of the country refused to do or could not do.  However, me and my fellow veterans DID SERVE. 

Now the SVA and other veteran-based groups and associations need to do something for me and other veterans who have been bamboozled by our own government leaders (e.g., ship commanders; post commanders, recruiters, etc....); and that is to right any wrongs that have befallen my fellow veterans as it relates to educational benefits and any other needs they may have.  

Semper Fortis,

Dr. Nick C. Cicchino 
US Navy (1979-1983)
US Air Force (1977-1978)
